{"title_page": "Alexandra Hospital (Redditch)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name = Alexandra Hospital\n| Org/Group = [[Worcestershire Acute Hospitals NHS Trust]]\n| Image = Alexandra Hospital Main Entrance - geograph.org.uk - 1717432.jpg\n| Caption = Alexandra Hospital\n| map_type = Worcestershire\n| map_caption = Shown in Worcestershire\n| latitude = <!-- used only for adding a map, with map_type -->\n| longitude = <!-- used only for adding a map, with map_type -->\n| Logo = <!-- optional -->\n| Location = [[Redditch]]\n| Region = [[Worcestershire]]\n| State = \n| Country = England\n| Coordinates = {{coord|52.2800|N|1.9127|W|display=inline, title}}\n| HealthCare = [[National Health Service (England)|NHS England]]\n| Type = District General\n| Speciality = <!-- if devoted to a speciality, i.e. not if has broad spectrum of specialities -->\n| Standards = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency = Yes\n| Affiliation = \n| Beds = \n| Founded = 1985\n| Closed = <!-- optional -->\n| Website = {{URL|www.worcsacute.nhs.uk}}\n| Wiki-Links = <!-- optional -->\n}}\n'''Alexandra Hospital''' is an acute general hospital in [[Redditch]], [[Worcestershire]], England. It is managed by the [[Worcestershire Acute Hospitals NHS Trust]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital, which replaced the Smallwood Hospital at Church Green,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/hospitalrecords/details.asp?id=902|title=Smallwood Hospital, Redditch|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> was completed in 1985.<ref name=bbc>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hereford-worcester-31485404|title=Alexandra Hospital resignations: Calls for government intervention|publisher=BBC|date=16 February 2015|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> It was officially opened by [[Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy|Princess Alexandra]] in April 1987.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worcsacute.nhs.uk/patient-information-and-leaflets/worcestershire-way/2147-worcestershire-way-july-2017-1/file|title=Celebrating 70 years of the NHS|page=4|date=1 July 2018|publisher=Worcestershire Way|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter four consultants left the hospital because of \"continuing uncertainty about the future of Redditch Hospital\" in February 2015, there were calls from a local pressure group for Government intervention.<ref name=bbc/> Then, in May 2015, a new modular operating theatre was opened at the hospital, thereby increasing capacity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worcesternews.co.uk/news/12936647.new-hospital-operating-theatre-will-mean-fewer-cancelled-ops/|title=New hospital operating theatre will mean fewer cancelled ops|date=7 May 2015|publisher=Worcester News|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official site|www.worcsacute.nhs.uk}}\n\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Worcestershire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        =Alexandra Hospital\n| Org/Group  = [[Worcestershire Acute Hospitals NHS Trust]]\n| Image       = Alexandra Hospital Main Entrance - geograph.org.uk - 1717432.jpg\n| Caption     = Alexandra Hospital\n| map_type    = Worcestershire\n| map_caption = Shown in Worcestershire\n| latitude    = <!-- used only for adding a map, with map_type -->\n| longitude   = <!-- used only for adding a map, with map_type -->\n| Logo        = <!-- optional -->\n| Location    = [[Redditch]]\n| Region      = [[Worcestershire]]\n| State       = \n| Country     = England\n| Coordinates = {{coord|52.2800|N|1.9127|W|display=inline, title}}\n| HealthCare  = [[National Health Service (England)|NHS England]]\n| Type        = District General\n| Speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality, i.e. not if has broad spectrum of specialities -->\n| Standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency   = \n| Affiliation = \n| Beds        = \n| Founded     = 1985\n| Closed      = <!-- optional -->\n| Website     = {{URL|www.worcsacute.nhs.uk}} \n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- optional -->\n}}\n'''Alexandra Hospital''' is an acute general hospital in [[Redditch]], [[Worcestershire]], England. It is managed by the [[Worcestershire Acute Hospitals NHS Trust]].\n\n==History==\nThe hospital, which replaced the Smallwood Hospital at Church Green,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/hospitalrecords/details.asp?id=902|title=Smallwood Hospital, Redditch|publisher=National Archives|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> was completed in 1985.<ref name=bbc>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hereford-worcester-31485404|title=Alexandra Hospital resignations: Calls for government intervention|publisher=BBC|date=16 February 2015|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> It was officially opened by [[Princess Alexandra, The Honourable Lady Ogilvy|Princess Alexandra]] in April 1987.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worcsacute.nhs.uk/patient-information-and-leaflets/worcestershire-way/2147-worcestershire-way-july-2017-1/file|title=Celebrating 70 years of the NHS|page=4|date=1 July 2018|publisher=Worcestershire Way|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter four consultants left the hospital because of \"continuing uncertainty about the future of Redditch Hospital\" in February 2015, there were calls from a local pressure group for Government intervention.<ref name=bbc/> Then, in May 2015, a new modular operating theatre was opened at the hospital, thereby increasing capacity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worcesternews.co.uk/news/12936647.new-hospital-operating-theatre-will-mean-fewer-cancelled-ops/|title=New hospital operating theatre will mean fewer cancelled ops|date=7 May 2015|publisher=Worcester News|accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official site|www.worcsacute.nhs.uk}}\n\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Worcestershire]]\n", "name_user": "KJD 0115gbr", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandra_Hospital_(Redditch)"}
{"title_page": "Save River (Africa)", "text_new": "{{Infobox river\n| name              = Save River\n| image             = Bridge over Savi River.JPG\n| image_size        = 300px\n| image_alt         = \n| image_caption     = A view of the Save in Mozambique\n| map               = Save Basin OSM.svg\n| map_size          = 300px\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = The Save Basin OSM\n| name_native       = \n| name_native_lang  = \n| name_other        = \n| source1_location  = South of [[Harare]], [[Zimbabwe]]\n| mouth_location    = [[Indian Ocean]]\n| progression       = \n| subdivision_type1 = Country\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Zimbabwe]], [[Mozambique]]\n| location          = \n| etymology         = \n| length            = {{convert|400|mi|km|abbr=on}}\n| source1_elevation =\n| mouth_elevation   =\n| discharge1_avg    =\n| basin_size        = {{convert|106,420|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} \n| river_system      = \n| tributaries_left  = \n| tributaries_right = \n| waterbodies       =\n| custom_label      =\n| custom_data       =\n}}\n\nThe '''Save River''', or '''Sabi River''' ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: ''Rio Save'') is a {{convert|400|mi|km|abbr=on}} river of southeastern Africa, flowing through [[Zimbabwe]] and [[Mozambique]].<ref name=\"b\"/><ref name=\"c\"/> The river has its source in Zimbabwe, some {{convert|80|km|mi|abbr=on}} south of [[Harare]], then flows south and then east, from the Zimbabwean highveld to its confluence with the [[Odzi River]]. It then turns south, drops over the Chivirira (\u201cPlace of Boiling\u201d) Falls, and flows down the western side of Zimbabwe's Eastern Highlands forming a dry river valley in the rain shadow of these mountains. It is joined by the [[Runde River]] or Lundi at the Mozambique border, forming a dramatic confluence at Mahenya. It then crosses Mozambique to flow into the [[Indian Ocean]] at about 21\u00b0S.\n\nThe Save River provided irrigation for sugar plantation, but now supports the cultivation of citrus, cotton, rice, and wheat. It is also a source of small-scale fishing for the local population.<ref name=\"b\"/><ref name=\"c\"/>\n\nIt divides Mozambique [[Public administration|administratively]], [[politics|politically]], [[ethnology|ethnically]] and [[ecology|ecologically]]:\n\n* During the [[colony|colonial]] era, the whole area south of the Save was considered a [[province]] of Mozambique; presently, the Save separates the provinces of [[Gaza Province|Gaza]] and [[Inhambane]] to the south, from those of [[Manica Province|Manica]] and [[Sofala]] to the north:\n* Politically, the \u201csouth-of-the-Save\u201d can be considered the stronghold of [[Frelimo]], while the region immediately to the north is, in general, more supportive of [[Renamo]];\n* The Save separates the [[ethnic group]]s that are native speakers of  [[Shangaan]] (or Xi-Tsonga), to the south, from those that speak languages of the [[Shona language|Shona]] group in the north;\n* Ecologically, as the Save flows into the [[Indian Ocean]], its mouth corresponds to the separation of [[tropical]] marine [[ecosystem]]s, to the north, from the [[subtropical]]; the terrestrial ecosystems show less variation along the coastal plain north and south of the river, but inland where the [[Chimanimani Mountains]] start, a [[montane forest]] develops, which is completely different from the forests found in the south.\n\nThe delta of the Save River includes mangrove forests which span approximately {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=on}} on the Indian Ocean coast. Villagers in the delta basin use the mangrove forests for timber and as a place for small-scale fishing. The ecology of the lower Save River basin has been affected by cyclones, flooding, erosion, and sea-level rise.<ref name=\"c\"/>\n\nHistorically it was a transport route for gold and trade goods between the coast and the hinterland occupied by the civilisation of [[Great Zimbabwe]] in the 13th and 14th centuries AD.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"b\">[http://www.britannica.com/place/Sabi-River Sabi River]</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"c\">{{cite journal | last1 = Massuanganhe | first1 = El\u00eddio A. | last2 = Macamo | first2 = Celia | last3 = Westerberg | first3 = Lars-Ove | last4 = Salom\u00e3o | first4 = Bandeira | last5 = Mavume | first5 = Alberto | last6 = Ribeiro | first6 = Eunice | year = 2015 | title = Deltaic coasts under climate-related catastrophic events \u2013 Insights from the Save River delta, Mozambique | journal = Ocean & Coastal Management | publisher = Elsevier | volume = 116 | pages = 331-340 | doi = 10.1016/j.ocecoaman.2015.08.008}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Rivers of Zimbabwe}}\n{{Rivers of Mozambique}}\n{{coord|-20.904169|35.062752|display=title|format=dms}}\n\n[[Category:Save River (Africa)| ]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Mozambique]]\n[[Category:International rivers of Africa]]\n[[Category:Geography of Gaza Province]]\n[[Category:Geography of Inhambane Province]]\n[[Category:Geography of Manica Province]]\n[[Category:Geography of Sofala Province]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox river\n| name              = Save River\n| image             = Bridge over Savi River.JPG\n| image_size        = 300px\n| image_alt         = \n| image_caption     = A view of the Save in Mozambique\n| map               = Save Basin OSM.svg\n| map_size          = 300px\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = The Save Basin OSM\n| name_native       = \n| name_native_lang  = \n| name_other        = \n| source1_location  = South of [[Harare]], [[Zimbabwe]]\n| mouth_location    = [[Indian Ocean]]\n| progression       = \n| subdivision_type1 = Country\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Zimbabwe]], [[Mozambique]]\n| location          = \n| etymology         = \n| length            = {{convert|400|mi|km|abbr=on}}\n| source1_elevation =\n| mouth_elevation   =\n| discharge1_avg    =\n| basin_size        = {{convert|106,420|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} \n| river_system      = \n| tributaries_left  = \n| tributaries_right = \n| waterbodies       =\n| custom_label      =\n| custom_data       =\n}}\n\nThe '''Save River''', or '''Sabi River''' ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]: ''Rio Save'') is a {{convert|400|mi|km|abbr=on}} river of southeastern Africa, flowing through [[Zimbabwe]] and [[Mozambique]].<ref name=\"b\"/><ref name=\"c\"/> The river has its source in Zimbabwe, some {{convert|80|km|mi|abbr=on}} south of [[Harare]], then flows south and then east, from the Zimbabwean highveld to its confluence with the [[Odzi River]]. It then turns south, drops over the Chivirira (\u201cPlace of Boiling\u201d) Falls, and flows down the western side of Zimbabwe's Eastern Highlands forming a dry river valley in the rain shadow of these mountains. It is joined by the [[Runde River]] or Lundi at the Mozambique border, forming a dramatic confluence at Mahenya. It then crosses Mozambique to flow into the [[Indian Ocean]] at about 21\u00b0S.\n\nThe Save River provided irrigation for sugar plantation, but now supports the cultivation of citrus, cotton, rice, and wheat. It is also a source of small-scale fishing for the local population.<ref name=\"b\"/><ref name=\"c\"/>\n\nIt divides Mozambique [[Public administration|administratively]], [[politics|politically]], [[ethnology|ethnically]] and [[ecology|ecologically]]:\n\n* During the [[colony|colonial]] era, the whole area south of the Save was considered a [[province]] of Mozambique; presently, the Save separates the provinces of [[Gaza Province|Gaza]] and [[Inhambane]] to the south, from those of [[Manica Province|Manica]] and [[Sofala]] to the north:\n* Politically, the \u201csouth-of-the-Save\u201d can be considered the stronghold of [[Frelimo]], while the region immediately to the north is, in general, more supportive of [[Renamo]];\n* The Save separates the [[ethnic group]]s that are native speakers of  [[Shangaan]] (or Xi-Tsonga), to the south, from those that speak languages of the [[Shona language|Shona]] group in the north;\n* Ecologically, as the Save flows into the [[Indian Ocean]], its mouth corresponds to the separation of [[tropical]] marine [[ecosystem]]s, to the north, from the [[subtropical]]; the terrestrial ecosystems show less variation along  the coastal plain north and south of the river, but inland where the [[Chimanimani]] mountain range starts, a [[montane forest]] develops, which is completely different from the forests found in the south.\n\nThe delta of the Save River includes mangrove forests which span approximately {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=on}} on the Indian Ocean coast. Villagers in the delta basin use the mangrove forests for timber and as a place for small-scale fishing. The ecology of the lower Save River basin has been affected by cyclones, flooding, erosion, and sea-level rise.<ref name=\"c\"/>\n\nHistorically it was a transport route for gold and trade goods between the coast and the hinterland occupied by the civilisation of [[Great Zimbabwe]] in the 13th and 14th centuries AD.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"b\">[http://www.britannica.com/place/Sabi-River Sabi River]</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"c\">{{cite journal | last1 = Massuanganhe | first1 = El\u00eddio A. | last2 = Macamo | first2 = Celia | last3 = Westerberg | first3 = Lars-Ove | last4 = Salom\u00e3o | first4 = Bandeira | last5 = Mavume | first5 = Alberto | last6 = Ribeiro | first6 = Eunice | year = 2015 | title = Deltaic coasts under climate-related catastrophic events \u2013 Insights from the Save River delta, Mozambique | journal = Ocean & Coastal Management | publisher = Elsevier | volume = 116 | pages = 331-340 | doi = 10.1016/j.ocecoaman.2015.08.008}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{Rivers of Zimbabwe}}\n{{Rivers of Mozambique}}\n{{coord|-20.904169|35.062752|display=title|format=dms}}\n\n[[Category:Save River (Africa)| ]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Zimbabwe]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Mozambique]]\n[[Category:International rivers of Africa]]\n[[Category:Geography of Gaza Province]]\n[[Category:Geography of Inhambane Province]]\n[[Category:Geography of Manica Province]]\n[[Category:Geography of Sofala Province]]\n", "name_user": "Tom Radulovich", "label": "safe", "comment": "link to Chimanimani Mountains", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Save_River_(Africa)"}
